"Pylorus and proximal duodenum","Greater curvature of stomach"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edistal oesophagus and the superior part of the lesser curvature of the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by the left gastric artery, It ascends to supply the distal oesophagus and then descends along the lesser curvature of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal jejunum and duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by branches of the superior mesenteric artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric fundus and cardia\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by short gastric arteries from the splenic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epylorus and proximal duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by the gastroduodenal artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater curvature of stomach\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the right and left gastroepiploic arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe three main branches from the coeliac trunk are the left gastric, common hepatic, and splenic arteries. Together these vessels supply the foregut derivatives from the distal oesophagus to the second part of the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The coeliac trunk supplies the foregut derivatives from the distal oesophagus to the second part of duodenum.","The coeliac trunk divides into three main branches: left gastric, common hepatic, and splenic arteries.","The left gastric artery supplies the distal oesophagus and lesser curvature of the stomach."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61883"}}